<paragraph blockId="10.[264,1325,284,630]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Etymology. 
<taxonomicName box="[468,525,484,509]" class="Insecta" family="Polycentropodidae" genus="Polycentropus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="silex">
<emphasis box="[468,525,484,509]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Silex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is Latin for flint, a pure form of microcrystalline quartz (silicate) commonly found in limestone rock. We name this species “ 
<taxonomicName box="[982,1042,524,550]" class="Insecta" family="Polycentropodidae" genus="Polycentropus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="silex">silex</taxonomicName>
” to honor Dr. Oliver S. Flint, Jr. of the 
<collectingCountry box="[448,500,564,590]" name="United States of America" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">U.S.</collectingCountry>
National Museum of Natural History, Washington, DC, for his many contributions to world trichopterology.
</paragraph>
